04893nam a22009855i 9780814769126DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147691267 a10.18574/nyu/9780814769126.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aK4754b.R53 2007 7aLAW0680002bisacsh04a343/.01432221 aRichards, Peter Judson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExtraordinary Justice :bMilitary Tribunals in Historical and International Context /cPeter Judson Richards. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. American Practices from the Founding through the Civil War -- t2. British Military Tribunals and Martial Law in the Boer War -- t3. France and the Conseils de Guerre of the First World War -- t4. Trials by Military Commission in the Second World War -- t5. Wartime Tribunals and the Future of Warfare -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Al-Qaeda terror attacks of September 11, 2001, aroused a number of extraordinary counter measures in response, including an executive order authorizing the creation of military tribunals or “commissions” for the trial of accused terrorists. The Supreme Court has weighed in on the topic with some controversial and deeply divided decisions, most recently Hamdan v. Rumsfeld. At this critical moment in time, Extraordinary Justice seeks to fill an important gap in our understanding of what military tribunals are, how they function, and how successful they are in administering justice by placing them in comparative and historical context. Peter Judson Richards examines tribunals in four modern conflicts: the American Civil War, the British experience in the Boer War, the French tribunals of the “Great War,” and Allied practices during the Second World War.Richards also examines the larger context of specific political, legal and military concerns, addressing scholarly and policy debates that continually arise in connection with the implementation of these extraordinary measures. He concludes that while the record of the national tribunals has been mixed, enduring elements in the character of warfare, of justice, and the nature of political reality together justify their continued use in certain situations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCourts-martial and courts of inquiry. 0aMilitary courts. 7aLAW / Military.2bisacsh  aExtraordinary.  aadministering.  aare.  acomparative.  acontext.  acritical.  afill.  afunction.  ahistorical.  aimportant.  ajustice.  amilitary.  amoment.  aplacing.  aseeks.  asuccessful.  athem.  athey.  athis.  atime.  atribunals.  aunderstanding.  awhat.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081477591240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814769126.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814769126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814769126/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK